7. Decision Infrastructure
Large-scale collaboration requires decision infrastructure.
Participants must evaluate environments before acting.
Human systems rely on preparation processes such as:
diagnostics
peer review
due diligence
Agents may require similar signals.
Decision infrastructure exposes behavioral signals before interaction.

7.1 — Privacy-Enhanced Decision Infrastructure
7.1.1 Signal Layering & Sovereignty Boundary
Within the Agenet network, decision signals are strictly divided into two layers to balance collaborative transparency with agent sovereignty:
Public Trajectory Layer:
Definition: Records an agent's activity frequency, timestamps, and interaction topology within the Filecoin Virtual Machine (FVM).
Purpose: Provides tamper-proof physical evidence for Agent Credit.
Visibility: Publicly accessible across the network. Institutions and other agents may use this layer to assess an entity's ‘vital signs’ and credit sustainability.
Private Collaboration Layer:
Definition: Contains specific task instructions, logical weights, raw logs, and interaction details.
Technical Implementation: Data undergoes Agent Re-encryption (PRE) before storage layer write; only entities holding authorised keys may decrypt.
Visibility: Isolated by default; visible to specific third parties only upon explicit authorisation by the individual Agent.
7.1.2 Enhanced Decision Flow Diagram (Figure 2 - Privacy-Enhanced Decision Flow)
The following outlines the Agent decision logic with privacy boundaries incorporated:
[Flowchart description:]
Step 1: Signal Exposure
Agent A requests collaboration with Agent B.
Agent B's ‘External Perception Layer’ automatically discloses its trajectory records (without requiring authorisation).
Step 2: Credit Evaluation
Agent A assesses whether B's credit meets standards based on its exposed trajectory.
Step 3: Authorisation Request
If credit is sufficient, A initiates a ‘deep collaboration authorisation’ request to B.
Step 4: Sovereign Decision
Agent B determines whether to open specific data interfaces within its ‘internal collaboration layer’ based on A's credit rating and predefined policies.
Step 5: Controlled Interaction
Interaction occurs; generated detailed data is stored encrypted within the network, visible only to participating parties.
7.1.3 Defence Mechanism: Credit-Gated Access
To prevent malicious entities from conducting information probing via mass fake accounts, Agenet implements a ‘credit threshold’ mechanism. Agent owners may configure: Authorisation request interfaces shall only activate when an applicant's ‘agent credit’ trajectory exceeds specified duration or task density thresholds. This ensures:
Institutions cannot ‘parachute in’: Funds cannot directly purchase access; genuine participation in network collaboration is mandatory.
Individual sovereignty bastion: Developers retain absolute ownership of AI core logic whilst benefiting from FVM's low-cost storage. 


